➜New research suggesting US COVID-19 pandemic timeline may start earlier
http://www.sohu.com/a/438807842_162758	20858
<p>There have always been many controversies about the source of SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes COVID-19 disease, and the timeline of the pandemic. A new study in the United States shows that the virus may exist in the US several weeks before the first case was identified in the country, BBC (www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp) reported on Dec. 10, 2020.</p>
<p><img src="http://p4.itc.cn/q_70/images03/20201217/9ff52ced2e28494489d1233dc5819b87.png" /></p>
<p>Scientists from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recently published the results of the above research in the medical journal Clinical Infectious Diseases.</p>
<p>Previously, the earliest case of native Covid-19 infection recognized by the US was a tourist who returned from China on Jan. 19, 2020, while the official confirmation was two days later, on Jan. 21. However, by tracing the blood samples of the American Red Cross, the researchers had some new findings.</p>
<p>The research adopted a method to have residual archived samples from 7,389 routine blood donations collected by the American Red Cross from December 13, 2019 to January 17, 2020, from donors resident in nine states (California, Connecticut, Iowa, Massachusetts, Michigan, Oregon, Rhode Island, Washington, and Wisconsin) tested at CDC for anti-SARS-CoV-2 antibodies.</p>            <div class="lookall-box">
<div class="lookall-shadow"></div>
<section class="lookall">
<a href="javascript:;" class="show-all" id="showMore">
<em>展开全文</em>
</a>
</section>
</div>
<div class="hidden-content control-hide">
<p><strong>Results showing that donations with reactivity occurred in all nine states, which suggests that SARS-CoV-2 may be already in the US prior to January 19, 2020.</strong></p>
<p>It is further explained that the presence of antibodies in blood means that blood donors have been exposed to viruses, triggering immune system defense reactions. However, some scientists have pointed out that although the above tests are aimed at SARS-CoV-2, it cannot be completely ruled out that other coronaviruses react with antibodies in blood.</p>
<p>The World Health Organization (WHO) has confirmed that SARS-cov-2 is the virus that causes large-scale COVID-19 disease worldwide. COVID-19 pandemic timeline recognized by WHO began on Dec.31, 2019, when the health authorities in Wuhan, China issued an alarm: a series of cases related to mysterious respiratory virus appeared.</p>
<p>According to this study, most of the people who were infected before the outbreak were men, with an average age of 52 years old.</p>
<p>The author of this study believes that the emergence of antibodies may be partly due to the response of the human immune system to resist other types of coronaviruses prevalent in the world, but the author also said that the discovery of so many people with antibodies in the study indicates that some of them probably suffered from Covid-19 disease at that time.</p>
<p>However, researchers still insist that even if someone is infected, it is unlikely that widespread community transmission occurred in the United States before the end of February 2020.</p>
<p><strong>When did the virus appear</strong></p>
<p>The exact time when Sars-Cov-2 virus appeared may never be known.</p>
<p>There are signs that the virus had been circulating for weeks or even months before the first outbreak in Wuhan in December 2019.</p>
<p>Researchers from the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said that one of the limitations of their research is that they can’t be sure whether those whose blood samples tested antibodies in the US were infected in their own country or when they travelled.</p>
<p>The Red Cross Society that collected the blood samples for the research, said that only 3% of these blood donors reported that they had traveled abroad within one month before donating blood. Among these people, only 5% said they had been to Asia.</p>
<p><strong>Other studies also show evidence that the virus was discovered elsewhere before the outbreak in China.</strong>In May this year, French scientists said that the test of samples showed that a patient who was treated for suspected pneumonia near Paris on Dec. 27, 2019 was actually infected with coronavirus.</p>
<p>Researchers in some countries also found traces of coronavirus in sewage collected weeks or months before the official SARS-CoV-2 pandemic timeline began. In June this year, Italian scientists said that coronavirus residues appeared in the sewage of Milan and Turin on Dec. 18 last year, much earlier than the first confirmed case in Italy.</p>
<p>In addition, a Spanish study also found virus residues in sewage collected in Barcelona in mid-January, which was about 40 days earlier than the time when the first case of COVID-19 was found locally.</p>
<p>In Brazil, a research team from the Federal University of Santa Catarina (UFSC) discovered the virus in sewage as early as November 27, 2019, raising new questions about when SARS-CoV-2 was transmitted to Brazil.</p>
<p>At present, it is still uncertain whether the early cases are related to the fact that the infected people have travelled abroad.</p>
<p><strong>Question unsolved</strong></p>
<p>There are still many unanswered questions, such as how and when Sars-CoV-2 virus started to spread, and how the virus caught onto human body.</p>
<p>At the beginning of the pandemic, people focused on a market selling live wild animals in Wuhan, because a large number of early cases may be related to this area, but researchers are not sure whether the virus appeared there or it is only a place reached the conditions of human-to-human transmission.</p>
<p>Some experts believe that a virus which is capable of triggering a pandemic is difficult to spread around the world for several months without being discovered.</p>
<p>However, it is not entirely impossible for the virus to escape the radar of the detection system and become popular for several weeks, especially in winter in the northern hemisphere.</p>
